04579nam a22005895i 9780520917750DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209177507 a10.1525/97805209177502doi  a(DE-B1597)648090  a(OCoLC)1419788920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aTF24.C3bD48 1994eb 7aHIS0361402bisacsh04a385/.097941 aDeverell, William F, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRailroad Crossing :bCalifornians and the Railroad, 1850-1910 /cWilliam F Deverell; ed. by William F. Deverell. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Varieties of Railroad Antagonism -- t1. "What Is This Railroad to Do for Us?" -- t2. "California Netted with Iron Tracks" -- t3. A Volcano at Arty Moment: The Pullman Strike in California -- t4. The Los Angeles "Free Harbor Fight" -- t5. Pens as Swords: Fiction, Nonfiction, and Railroad Opposition -- t6. "Let Us Agitate and Agitate": Progressives and the Railroad -- tEpilogue: Building an Octopus -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNothing so changed nineteenth-century America as did the railroad. Growing up together, the iron horse and the young nation developed a fast friendship. Railroad Crossing is the story of what happened to that friendship, particularly in California, and it illuminates the chaos that was industrial America from the middle of the nineteenth century through the first decade of the twentieth.Americans clamored for the progress and prosperity that railroads would surely bring, and no railroad was more crucial for California than the transcontinental line linking East to West. With Gold Rush prosperity fading, Californians looked to the railroad as the state's new savior. But social upheaval and economic disruption came down the tracks along with growth and opportunity.Analyzing the changes wrought by the railroad, William Deverell reveals the contradictory roles that technology and industrial capitalism played in the lives of Americans. That contrast was especially apparent in California, where the gigantic corporate "Octopus"—the Southern Pacific Railroad—held near-monopoly status. The state's largest employer and biggest corporation, the S.P. was a key provider of jobs and transportation—and wielder of tremendous political and financial clout.Deverell's lively study is peopled by a rich and disparate cast: railroad barons, newspaper editors, novelists, union activists, feminists, farmers, and the railroad workers themselves. Together, their lives reflect the many tensions—political, social, and economic—that accompanied the industrial transition of turn-of-the-century America.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRailroadsxSocial aspectszCaliforniaxHistory. 0aRailroadszCaliforniaxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aState & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY). 4aUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh1 aDeverell, William F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020505540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091775040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917750/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles